    }
  ],
  "timestamp": "2026-01-03T12:00:00.000Z"
}
{{/code}}

== Job Commit Tracing ==

Every job records the git commit hash of the deployed code that ran it. This lets admins answer two operational questions:

* //Which version of the code ran this job?// — look at a single job's commit hash
* //Which jobs ran before/after a specific deploy?// — search by commit hash to list all matching jobs

=== How It Works ===

At API startup, the system resolves the current commit hash:

1. **##GIT_COMMIT## env var** — set by CI/CD at deployment (preferred for production)
2. **##git rev-parse HEAD##** — fallback for local development (3-second timeout; silently skipped if git is unavailable)
3. **##null##** — if neither is available (hash is absent on the job record)

The resolved hash is stored on every ##Job## row at creation time (column ##GitCommitHash##). Retry jobs capture the hash of the code that ran the retry, which may differ from the original job's hash — useful for spotting "this retry ran on a different build."

=== Find a Job's Commit Hash ===

**Via the UI (Job Detail page):**

1. Navigate to the job: ##/jobs/{jobId}##
2. Scroll to the //Quality// section at the bottom of the Report tab
3. The //Git commit// row appears in the admin panel (only visible when logged in as admin)
4. Click **Find jobs with this hash →** to immediately list all jobs that ran the same commit

**Via the API:**

{{code language="bash"}}
curl -H "X-Admin-Key: <your-key>" http://localhost:5000/v1/jobs/<jobId>
# Response includes: "gitCommitHash": "56ed040b4f7d3850..."
{{/code}}

Jobs created before this feature was deployed will have ##gitCommitHash: null##.

=== List Jobs by Commit Hash ===

**Via the Admin page:**

1. Navigate to ##/admin##
2. In the **Job Audit & Debugging** section, find the **Commit Hash Tracer**
3. Enter the full hash or any prefix (e.g. ##56ed040b##)
4. Click **Find Jobs** — results show job ID, status, creation time, and input preview
5. Click any row to open that job's detail page

**Via the API:**

{{code language="bash"}}
# Full hash
curl -H "X-Admin-Key: <key>" "http://localhost:5000/v1/jobs?gitHash=56ed040b4f7d3850289ccaae"

# Prefix search (returns all jobs whose hash starts with this prefix)
curl -H "X-Admin-Key: <key>" "http://localhost:5000/v1/jobs?gitHash=56ed040b"
{{/code}}

The ##gitHash## filter is admin-only (ignored without a valid ##X-Admin-Key##). It accepts lowercase hex characters and matches on prefix, so you can use an abbreviated hash from ##git log --oneline##.

=== Deployment Setup ===

For production, set the ##GIT_COMMIT## environment variable at deployment time:

{{code language="bash"}}
# Example: inject at Docker build
docker build --build-arg GIT_COMMIT=$(git rev-parse HEAD) .

# Example: set in the process environment (systemd, Kubernetes, etc.)
GIT_COMMIT=56ed040b4f7d3850289ccaae dotnet run
{{/code}}

Without ##GIT_COMMIT##, the API falls back to running ##git## at startup. This works in local dev but may return ##null## in production containers where git is not installed.

=== Troubleshooting ===

|= Symptom |= Likely Cause |= Fix
| ##gitCommitHash## is ##null## on all jobs | ##GIT_COMMIT## not set and ##git## unavailable at startup | Set ##GIT_COMMIT## env var in the deployment environment
| ##gitCommitHash## missing from API response | Caller is not an admin | Include ##X-Admin-Key## header in the request
| Old jobs all show ##null## | Feature was added after those jobs ran | Expected — backfill is not automatic; ##null## means "recorded before this feature shipped"

== Security Notes ==

* The admin pages should be protected in production environments
* API keys are never displayed in the UI, only validation status
* Test responses are minimal to avoid exposing sensitive data
